The contribution of volunteerism to countries’ GDP cannot be underestimated. In Kenya, volunteerism contributes to about 3.6 per cent of the GDP according to research commissioned by the State Department for Social Protection in 2017.
Commemoration of the 2020 International Volunteer Day (IVD) recognised their contribution. In the region, governments, UN partners, academia, civil society and volunteer-involving organisations enumerated the benefits of volunteerism, like support to skilling where capacity gaps exist across the development context; support to service delivery, particularly in far-flung areas and ensuring no one is left behind in building community resilience.
Noting that volunteers at times work in challenging environments, they also advocated support and care for them. Anecdotes from volunteer-involving organisations showed that online volunteering works just as well as on-site volunteering, where extenuating circumstances limit the latter. 
Further evidence showed that the nimbleness of local volunteerism — flexibility, swiftness to act and the ability to self-organise — were attributes that came in handy in response to Covid-19.
With Covid-19 stretching the resilience of our communities, let us fight back by mobilising our volunteer spirits and overcome this pandemic.



